Speaking during the launch at the Jamhuri Stadium, the deputy minister said the government was ready to host this historic event and a breeding ground to unearth new talents.At least 20,000 students are expected to gather in Mwanza next month, when the region play host to UMISSETA and Inter-Primary Games, UMITASHUMTA. And, in run up to the event, Jaffo took the opportunity to remind all councils in the country to make sure that sports programmes in schools were compulsory and improved. I take this opportunity to remind council directors, educational officers from all levels to ensure our pupils and students are allowed to take part in sports programmes in schools. This is compulsory not optional. Teachers should not use time allocated for sports programmes to teach other lessons, he warned.He described sports as among important ingredient in stimulating and sharpening students brain, keep them fit and healthy, strengthen relations and nationalism. Jaffo has commended Coca-Cola for investing in UMISSETA Games, urging other companies to emulate from the beverage company. Coca-Cola has agreed to sponsor UMISSETA Games from 2016 to 2018 by bankrolling meals expenses worth 50m/- during the competitions every year, they will also provide water and distribute sports gears to all secondary schools which is quite generous and we are grateful for their enormous contribution, said Jaffo.The deputy minister added that Coca-Cola has set a good example by investing in secondary school sports, saying the competitions are the foundation of molding future reputable athletes On her side, Coca-Cola Representative, Pamela Lugenge, assured the government and participants that the firm will continue supporting youth s efforts in developing their career in sports. We will continue to support the government s initiatives as well as supporting youth in developing their career in sports through sponsoring various competitions including Copa-UMESSETA Game, she said.She thanked the government through the Regional Administration and Local Government ministry and the ministry of Information, Culture, Arts and Sport as well as the National Sports Council (NSC) for supporting Coca- Cola s initiatives.